So as a warning, do not approach this movie or book in the hopes of expanding your knowledge of God, The Trinity, or His Kingdom. Even despite it being labeled fiction, this book still leads God's children astray as they adopt its' false ideology and representations of the Biblical truth. If you want to be more enlightened on any issue pertaining to God, go the Bible, which is literally God's Word.

text: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ SPOILER WARNING ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  Christians don't like this film  now that may not be a surprise to anyone familiar with 'The Shack', but for those who aren't: the reason Christians reject this story is because the nice black lady 'Elousia', the middle-eastern man, and the asian woman 'Sarayu' are representations of the three persons of the Holy Trinity - God the Father, God the Son and God the Holy Spirit, respectively  of course some people reading this might say; "i'm a christian, i think the shack is a beautiful interpretation of whom God is and how God wants us to live" but i'm afraid they aren't really christians - because anyone who relies on this story to help them understand God, is rejecting the words of Scripture where God constantly refers to Himself in masculine pronouns and reveals Himself as Father  Jesus himself is recorded as speaking of both God the Father and God the Holy Spirit with masculine pronouns  perhaps you don't think this is a big deal, but God also reveals Himself in scripture as being very particular about how mankind represents Him - and we get the word 'Blasphemy' from the idea of giving a witness account in a court of law; and if one gives a false testimony in court, they are 'speaking evil' or 'blaspheming'  and since God goes out of His way in Scripture to refer to Himself in masculine terms, then to represent Him in any other way is a misrepresentation, a false account, or a 'blasphemy'  so bearing in mind that the underlying premise to this whole story is a misrepresentation of whom God is, we then have to ask if the lessons this story teaches 'also' misrepresent what God demands of mankind?  the consensus of real christians is that yes, it does - and anyone who embraces the false god represented in The Shack is still on their way to Hell

text: This movie had so much potential. I was getting vibes of "Prisoners" from the first part of this trailer... A hard hitting, gritty reality driven story of pain and a bond between a man and his daughter... Then it went all fun time fantasy like something plucked straight out of a family Disney movie and it died from there on.   Be one type of movie or the other, don't try to splice the two. I appreciate that it's based on the book so this is the direction it follows but it could have remained true and gritty, his delusions didn't need to be so colourful and romanticised they could have gone dark, really dark the kind of darkness you would expect of a man's mind losing his daughter... Not a heartwarming fairy tale.

It's a good story about coping with the pain of loss and spiritual healing etc. However with books/films like this,  in the end I can't help but feel that  it's so far removed from reality. People often lose children, parents, siblings, spouses in horrible ways. text: Did not know this movie was coming - glad to see it!! Years ago, the book was extremely controversial in the Christian world - in fact friends and fellowships split harshly over it. Most of the haters couldn't get over a black woman representing a big part of God's nature and wisdom - they considered it 100% heresy - and many could not bear to finish reading the short book. But what I took from the book was totally different. The book dealt squarely with an "all too often" theme that the church is unable to successfully confront - and that is how is it possible to find/keep/return to "faith" in the midst of a terrible human tragedy (of the worst kind). This book takes on an event that would shatter the strongest faith, the kind of event that will always force the question "how a good God could possibly exist in such a mean, disgusting, terrible world."  A brave book. If the movie is 90% as good as the book, it will be an incredible flick.

text: So, I know this trailer had a hard time displaying the main plot points, therefore I will do so:  The Shack is based off of one of my most favorite novels of all time. It is about a man whose daughter was kidnapped, raped, and murdered in a small shack in the mountains. Months after, this man receives a letter from "God", inviting him back to the Shack.  There, he meets the trinity that is God. specifically, the black lady is God the father, the Asian is the Holy Spirit, and the man is Jesus.  It was a very touching story, and novel. But I do question its veracity as a film. Still, I know I'll see it, if only for my respect of the book.

text: I hope that this could be a good sincere faith-based movie.  I fear it will get to "preachy" and want to tie things up in a pretty little bow. Life doesn't, has never, and will never work that way. Faith, logic, spirituality, religion, whatever one personally holds to in order to get through the joys and pains of life is a common thread that all humans share. THAT is what could make this movie truly uplifting, rather than so much schlock designed to appease a target audience. I have no problem with a movie that might have a certain take on religion or spirituality. For example "What Dreams May Come". I'm not enough of a cinephile to give other international examples, though I'm sure there are many. Those perspectives are fine.  Just like any movie, it's how the story is told. Maybe I'm being too optimistic.

text: Young‚Äôs stereotypical characterization of the Father as a ‚Äúlarge beaming African-American woman,‚Äù the Son as a Jew with a large nose, and the Holy Spirit as a mysterious Asian female makes me more than a little queasy. Furthermore, virtually every theological heresy begins with a misconception of the nature of God. The Shack is no exception. After chiding those he believes to have misconceptions about the Trinity, Young proceeds to compromise, confuse, or outright contradict biblical orthodoxy. He pictures the Father bearing crucifixion scars as well as being incarnated in tandem with the Holy Spirit. In historic, biblical Christianity only the Son is incarnated and only the Son suffers and dies on the cross. Moreover, Young pontificates that Jesus ‚Äúhas never drawn upon his nature as God to do anything‚Äù (emphasis in original). Those who have read through the Bible will immediately recognize the falsity of this statement‚Äîparticularly with respect to the resurrection. For example, in John‚Äôs Gospel Jesus says, ‚ÄúThe reason my Father loves me is that I lay down my life‚Äîonly to take it up again. No one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord. I have authority to lay it down and authority to take it up again. This command I received from my Father‚Äù (John 10:17‚Äì18 NIV). Equally problematic is the fact that Young negates the notion of functional subordination within the Godhead. As the large beaming African-American woman in Young‚Äôs novel explains, the Trinity is ‚Äúin a circle of relationship, not a chain of Command.‚Ä¶Hierarchy would make no sense among us‚Äù (emphasis in original). In biblical orthodoxy, however, the incarnate Christ says, ‚ÄúI tell you the truth, the Son can do nothing by himself; He can do only what He sees his Father doing, because whatever the Father does the Son also does‚Äù (John 5:19 NIV). Put another way, functional hierarchy is not antithetical to ontological equality. Finally, Young has Jesus‚Äîthe Jew with the big nose‚Äîdeclaring, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not a Christian‚Äù and ‚ÄúI have no desire to make them [Buddhists, Mormons, Muslims, etc.) Christian.‚Äù Indeed, Young describes Christians as religious fanatics and part of a sinful world system. In sharp distinction, the followers of Christ adopted the word ‚ÄúChristian‚Äù in the midst of suffering and persecution. The apostle Peter, for example, writes, ‚ÄúIf you suffer as a Christian, do not be ashamed but praise God that you bear that name‚Äù (1 Pet. 4:16 NIV; cf. Acts 11:26). The fact that The Shack is being touted by those who take the sacred name of Christ upon their lips is a sad commentary on Christian discernment. text: 7-10-17  I've never wrote a Journal before. To think of my writing is humerus. For I'm dialysis. As I think to myself what is a point? Who would care of my voice in their ears? But laying next to my wife I realize maybe one day kids and wife would be a beneficial.   As laying next to my half. My mind slip away.......Have you ever wonder who god is? Have you ever stop and listen or even dare to question our creator? I don't know about every one. But I know I have. Some time I wish its as easy to write a letter to god. But if it where that easy. Then the question of life wouldn't be so complicated. We know we all think we focuses on god. We all reminds ourself and love ones. "We love god". But putting my foot out in the working world as my 1st truly honest business man. Starting from his humble start. In trailer and truck. With his last money he went back to construction. A busy humble small success. "I realized". I've forgotten about god. This long road path. With every step of the way some how I felt he is with me. All this I tell me self each time I see a penny on my road path. Reminding my self two word..."thank god for walking with me".  For tomorrow that meal for my family might be gone.  For the next 16 years with my wife. Some how we never starve. We manage to make day by day. With little improve each year. The rodeo was complicated and strive thought extreme complication. But who house is beautiful?  I look on FB, instagrame, every one house is beautiful happy like a dream. The wonderful 1000 friends or followers, The amazing party and event, the beautiful girlfriend, that crazy drugs life. That sexy outfit, forcing our eyes on the color, fabrics of life on medias. But I have forget to thank god.   It's take months of busy working. Focusing on the next step in life. It come down to one movie today that help me stop. And write this journal. "The shack"...the movies help me truly understand who god is. Thank you
author: Bless of dyslexic The Riddler of Arts
